				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Perhaps the answer is to create a level editor which knows almost nothing about what an NES game engine actually expects (except palette constraints)---that could be the job of a map compressor plugin. My level editor has a big uncompressed 2D grid of the smallest type of metatile, which is 2x2 nametable tiles. To generate data for a given scrolling engine, I write a map compressor plugin. It is the job of the plugin to find duplicate regions in the uncompressed map and create meta tiles expected by the target scrolling engine. The kinds of attributes supported by the meta tiles are constrained at the moment; if I were to re-write this level editor I would make that pluggable as well, or simply be a list of keyword: value pairs that the map compressor could play with as it sees fit. That way, if I come up with a more sophisticated game engine some day, I could add new attributes for slopes (for example) that a new map compressor could recognize and transform into a format that my new scrolling engine expects.
<br />
<br />So, if you tried something like the above, you could focus entirely on making a feature rich editor and not think too much about supporting any type of game engine. If I were you I'd create at least one example compressor and scrolling engine that could play the maps you create, though.</div>

